<subSubSection lastPageId="25" lastPageNumber="226" pageId="24" pageNumber="225" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="24" pageNumber="225">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,367,392]" pageId="24" pageNumber="225">Remarks.</emphasis>
A description of this species was given by 
<bibRefCitation author="Ghauri" box="[837,1004,367,392]" pageId="24" pageNumber="225" refString="Ghauri, M. S. K. (1971) Revision of the genus Nephotettix Matsumura (Homoptera, Cicadelloidea, Euscelidae) based on the type material. Bulletin of Entomological Research, 60 (3), 481 - 512. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1017 / s 0007485300040438" type="journal article" year="1971">
Ghauri (
<number box="[935,995,368,392]" pageId="24" pageNumber="225" value="1971.0">1971</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. Some variation is found as follows. Crown always without black band, but black markings of forewing vary (Plate V: A–H). Pygofer side usually distodorsal and distoventral corner round, spine 
<number box="[694,708,440,464]" pageId="24" pageNumber="225" value="1.0">1</number>
long, slim; other spines usually 
<quantity box="[1073,1117,439,464]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.016" pageId="24" pageNumber="225" unit="in" value="4.0">4 in</quantity>
number, short, but variation is found (
<figureCitation box="[261,353,476,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="26.[151,249,1788,1810]" captionTargetBox="[183,1432,250,1717]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[170,1456,241,1725]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 17. Nephotettix virescens (Distant). A – E: male pygofer side, lateral view; F: valve, ventral view; G – H: subgenital plate, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/226703/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="225">
Figs. 
<number box="[326,353,476,500]" pageId="24" pageNumber="225" value="17.0">17</number>
</figureCitation>
A–E); apophysis of style always elongate, but its shape varies (
<figureCitation box="[1081,1173,476,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="27.[151,249,1385,1407]" captionTargetBox="[209,1376,203,1361]" captionTargetId="figure@27.[203,1384,193,1368]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 18. Nephotettix virescens (Distant). A – C: style, dorsal view; D: connective, dorsal view; E: aedeagus, ventral view; F – G: aedeagus, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/226704/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="225">
Figs. 
<number box="[1146,1173,476,500]" pageId="24" pageNumber="225" value="18.0">18</number>
</figureCitation>
A–C). This is the most easily distinguished 
<taxonomicName box="[381,510,512,536]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Nephotettix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="225" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[381,510,512,536]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="225">Nephotettix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. The most important feature is the completely unmarked crown with a distinct furrow (Plate V: A–H).
</paragraph>
